#note Pretty interesting pre-endgame. My logic was that I could only see LOOPIEST and KEITLOAS as bingos, and by covering the most dangerous scoring spot at A1 and keeping IN so I can get out next turn. The competitor play that Josh suggested is MINNIE at M3 which would've blocked his game-winning bingo. However, MINNIE can lose if I don't draw a good enough out or if I pull two consonants. MISER (and MERISM, same idea at 9G) wins 31/36 versus 29.5/36 for MINNIE in a vacuum. HOWEVER, Cedric's last play pretty much tells me his exact rack - if he had AELIST, he would've played FOLIATES; EILOST, FOLKIEST; EIOPST, POOFIEST, and AILOST, FLOKATIS. That basically means he has AELPST, EILPST or ELOPST. That leaves the possible two-tile combos in the bag as AA, AIx2, AOx2 and IO. I lose to IO no matter what, but MINNIE beats AA and should be my play here.
>cedric_lewis: EILOPST 2G L.OPIEST +82 516
